Strategic Question

Using both 2019 and 2020 Happiness Reports datasets. The questions is, whether there are variables in relation to gdp_per_capita, that give a strong relationship, and if the gdp_per_capita of a country can be predicted.

Summarising in Numeric Data

Anomalies in Numeric investigation

Visualization between variables relations

This heatmap shows the correlation coefficients between each and every the variable. The more darker the shade of blue is, the greater the strength of the positive correlation, and the more darker the shade of red is the more correlated the greater the strength of the negative correlation.

NB: The relationship between health and gdp_per_capita, has the greatest positive correlation.

  1. Countries above 0.75 of gdp_per_capita have a happiness_score from 5 and above

  2. Most european countries have a gdp_per_capita above 1.0

  3. Australian countries have a government trust exceeding 0.3

  4. Almost all african countries have a government trust below 0.2

Model Evaluation

Model on trainset

Residuals

Residual plot indicates that there is a slight curvature, so it is non-linear

Prediction

  • intercept = -0.3590075

  • slope = 0.249379

  • x-value/happiness_score = 8.201

  • prediction = (slope*x-value) + intercept

  • prediction = (0.249379*8.201) + ( -0.3590075)

  • prediction = 1.68615

    NB: The model predicts that a country will have a gdp_per_capita of 1.68615 if its happiness score is 8.201.
